  "prompt": "How much does IVF increase a woman's odds of having twins or multiple babies at once?",
  "response": "In vitro fertilization (IVF) has historically increased the likelihood of having twins or multiple births compared to natural conception. This is primarily because multiple embryos often used to be transferred to enhance the chances of a successful pregnancy. Historically, IVF led to multiple birth rates of about 20-30%, significantly higher than the natural occurrence of twins, which is about 1-2%.\n\nHowever, practices have evolved, and many fertility clinics now follow guidelines recommending the transfer of a single embryo when possible, especially in younger women or when a good-quality embryo is available. This approach, known as elective single embryo transfer (eSET), aims to reduce the risks associated with multiple births, such as premature birth and low birth weight.\n\nAs a result of these changes, the incidence of twins and higher-order multiples in IVF cases has decreased. But, IVF still presents a higher chance of multiples than natural conception, particularly when multiple embryos are transferred. It\u2019s important for individuals considering IVF to discuss with their healthcare providers their options and the associated risks.",
